'The sea is ours': landlocked Bolivia hopes court will reopen the path to the Pacific
Sailors patrolling a rigged naval office in La Paz.
Public buildings are flying an ocean blue flag.
At all naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the motto is: "The sea is ours".
It is a duty to win them back.
Throughout land-locked Bolivia, the memory of the coastline that the country had to cede to Chile after a bloody 19th-century resource conflict is still alive, as is the desire to sail the Pacific again.
That hope may have reached its highest point in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice, which is due to be delivered on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and is naturally looking forward to the outcome with positive prospects", said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians across the country will be watching the Court's ruling on large screens, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will argue in Bolivia's favor that Chile, after decades of heated talks, is obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
