"We are very close to returning to the Pacific", he vowed at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in favor of Bolivia, and even if it did, little would change.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no authority to grant Chilean territory and has indicated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice's ruling comes just six months after the final hearings indicates that the case was "not complicated", says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And the prospects for a positive outcome for Bolivia have certainly not improved, on the contrary, the situation may have worsened over the last four years.
"The case of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian government", Zárate said.
Morales' bellicose rhetoric has completely undermined all the goodwill that Chile may have had, she claimed.
Bolivia and Chile will at some point continue their talks, but it will be extremely difficult to talk further after this.
The two countries have not had an ambassador in each other's country since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, denies that the court's decision was unusually hasty.
On Monday, Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of international relations with Chile" and an opportunity to "end 139 years of disagreements, with mutual benefits", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who remains one of Latin America's most popular presidents, is using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
