John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland have an excellent record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with a series of further excellent exam results, and furthermore individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community-wide initiatives.
With over 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for continuing and higher education, their chosen career and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects at the forefront of schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to someone in a language they understand, you reach their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and bonds of trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year's examinations, we can deduce that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest pass rates within independent schools.
In all, 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages scored high.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS-affiliated schools, showed that 72 percent of students scored high (A) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students in German, 69 percent of students in French, and 63 percent of students in Spanish also scored A's.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as much as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 per cent of the barriers to filling jobs were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more and more jobs requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, having learned a second language will give him a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Direct communication with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an edge over the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, with French being the only language to stand out above 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is important for today's children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, schools choose the languages they teach.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK as they look ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future.
It cannot be denied that languages in a global business environment remain vital to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's got to be done right.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
