Harvard students take a course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is getting all students more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night and drink a lot of caffeine.
One professor found that students at the world's largest university often have no idea of the basics of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist affiliated with Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which, to his knowledge, is unique in the United States.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of my talk, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why am I only hearing this now, in my senior year?'
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being organized for the first time this year, will teach students the basics of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was determined that students were severely sleep-deprived during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, students see a picture of a bedroom, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise devices, and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, and the importance of a routine for sleep.
In another section, participants are told how lack of sleep increases the long-term risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Using a campus map with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to reflect on their daily routine.
We know that this will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we think they have a right to know all this, just as people have a right to know what the choice of cigarettes is doing to their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in studying overnight still exists, he says, and with modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an increasing problem.
Providing adequate, good-quality sleep should be the student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to write the course, having attended classes with the professor last year when he was a freshman at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make sure the course was available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar programme of study before coming to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, not just an alarm for getting up, but also to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" from electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, making it difficult to fall asleep.
