Bernard Vann: Clergyman and Victoria Cross recipient from WWI
The only Church of England clergyman to have won a Victoria Cross during World War I as a soldier is being honoured 100 years later in the town of his birth.
Lieutenant Colonel, the Reverend Bernard Vann was awarded the medal for the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt on 29 September 1918.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later, never knowing that he had been awarded Britain's highest military honour.
A memorial stone was unveiled by his two grandsons during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of the grandchildren, Michael Vann, said that it was "brilliantly symbolic" that the stone was unveiled exactly 100 years after the fact for which his grandfather had been honored.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in a very dense fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns".
He later rushed to the line of fire and led the line forward before running alone to a field gun and killing three members of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "something I know I can never guess, but also something that makes me feel humbled".
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also laid a wreath after the parade which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said that he "felt very honoured to be able to play a part in the parade", adding that "the bravery of a true hero is shown by the support he receives from a large number of people".
