And if the track itself isn't daunting enough, Mickelson will face the ever-accurate Francesco Molinari, winner of the British Open, in the ninth match on Sunday, who is tied with rookie Tommy Fleetwood to win all four matches this week.
If the Americans, who are four points behind at the start of the 12 singles matches, start well, Mickelson's match could be absolutely crucial.
Furyk has shown confidence in this man, even though he could hardly do otherwise.
"He fully understood the role he had today, slapped me on the back, put his arm around me and said he was ready for tomorrow", Furyk said.
"He has a lot of confidence.
He's in the Hall of Fame and he's done so much for these teams, in the past, and this week.
