Germany's new warship postponed again
The German Navy's newest frigate was supposed to enter service in 2014, replacing the aging Cold War-era warships, but it will take at least another year before it is ready, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the 'Rheinland-Pfalz', the lead ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit quoting a military spokesman.
The vessel was supposed to join the navy in 2014, but troubling problems after delivery have plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels ordered by the Navy in 2007 are to replace the obsolete Bremen-class frigates.
As far as we know, they have a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles and some form of stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic features.
Other important features are longer maintenance cycles, it should be possible to deploy the newest frigates up to two years in a row, far from home ports.
However, the continuing delays mean that the advanced warships, which are intended to enable Germany to project its power overseas, are already obsolete by the time they are put into service, notes Die Zeit.
The fatal frigate F125 made headlines last year when the German navy officially refused to commission the vessel and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy has sent a ship back to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons behind this return, but German media cited a number of crucial 'software and hardware flaws' that would render the warship useless if deployed on a combat mission.
Software defects were particularly important because the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels are operated by a crew of about 120 seamen, half the manpower of the older Bremen-class frigates.
It was also clear that the ship was suffering from severe overweight, which would reduce performance and limit the Navy's ability to carry out further upgrades.
The 'Rheinland-Pfalz' weighs 7,000 tons, which is twice as much as ships of a similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the price tag for the entire project, including the training of the crew, is also a problem.
It is said that this has reached a staggering €3.1 billion, compared with the original €2.2 billion.
The problems facing the newest frigates are made all the more important by recent warnings that the German navy is losing power.
Earlier this year Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the parliamentary defense committee in Germany, admitted that the navy actually "has a shortage of deployable ships".
The official said that the problem has grown over time like a snowball, as old ships were taken out of service but no replacement vessels were delivered.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates were available for the navy.
National Trust eavesdropping on the secret life of bats
New research being conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation efforts.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common and small dwarf bats, the brown great-eared bats and the water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to monitor the bat's activities throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's cries and what kind of what it does.
A map of the habitat and a report are then produced to provide a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser at the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of grasslands and how best to maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as can fly traps and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts who regularly conduct investigations, inspections of accommodation and sometimes rescue operations.
In fact, the organization has set up the first and only bat sanctuary in Scotland at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for the bats.
"Here in Threave we have a great environment for bats", he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But there's so much we don't know about bats, and so the work we're doing here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive".
He stresses the importance of bat control before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unintentional destruction of a nest could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, potentially wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or to destroy their habitat.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to contribute to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and many of our species simply don't know how their populations are doing".
