Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup by defeating the US team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at the Le Golf National golf course southwest of Paris in France.
The U.S. has now lost six straight times on European soil, and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won the title when the Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team scored the required 14.5 points to beat the USA.
The star of the American team, Phil Mickelson, who had been struggling for most of the tournament, dropped his long shot from the tee into the water at par 3, hole 16, conceding his loss to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari excelled in all his rounds, becoming one of only four players to ever go 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current form in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was sent off by the European team's lowest scorer, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark, with 5 holes down and 4 holes to play.
The highest-ranked player in the world rankings, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 holes down and 1 hole to play Ian Poulter of Great Britain, who may have played his last match in the Ryder Cup.
Spanishman Segrio Garcia, an eight-time Ryder Cup veteran, became the best European player of all time with 25.5 career points.
"I don't cry so quickly, but today I can't help it.
It's been a rough year.
I'm so grateful to Thomas for selecting me and believing in me.
I'm so glad we got the trophy back.
It's about the team, and I'm happy that I could help,' said an emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passes the torch to his compatriot, John Ram, who beat American legend Tiger Woods by two holes down and one hole to go in the singles game on Sunday.
"The enormous pride I feel for beating Tiger Woods, I've been following that guy all my life growing up", said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four games in France and now has a record of 13-21-3 in the Ryder Cup.
A strange statistic from one of the greatest players of all time, winner of 14 major championships, second only to Jack Nicklaus.
The U.S. team struggled to find the fairways over the weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played at a high level throughout the tournament.
The American captain, Jim Furyk, said after the disappointing performance of his team: "I'm proud of these guys, they fought.
For a short time this morning we have made Europe a little more difficult.
We resisted.
All due respect to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 players on his team played very well.
We're gonna regroup, and I'm gonna work with the PGA and our Ryder Cup committee, and we're gonna look forward.
I love these 12 boys and I'm proud to be their captain.
You have to take your hat off to the opponent.
We've been cheated".
Red glow update: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota counties.
The most recent report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission shows an overall decline in Red Glut concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the USA).
The Committee believes that there are reports of fragmentary increases in Red Glory in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, which could indicate a decline in concentrations.
The Red Glow stretches along an average 200-mile coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
There are about 10 miles of patches off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
There's also been a Red Glow sighting in Pasco County.
There were medium concentrations reported for the coast of Pinellas County last week, low to high concentrations for the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations at or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are persistent reports of airway irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier counties.
In northwest Florida, there was no report of respiratory irritation in the past week.
